the original tale since it's known to every single Chinese since probably

top_comment.author: Kevin Wu

comments.text:
+Zeki Xu Aladin actually appeared first in "One Thousand and One Nights" 
and Pocahontas was real herself. There's enough historical evidence to 
support this.
comments.author: MultiGamingNetwork710

comments.text:
Frozen was based off of Hans Christian Andersen's tale, 'The Snow Queen'.
The Little Mermaid was based off of one of Hans Christian Andersen's 
stories.
Mulan was based off of the chinese story, Hua Mulan or 'The Ballad of 
Mulan'.
Pocahontas was based off of Jon Smith, one of the real plymouth pilgrims.
The Princess and the Frog was based off of a story by Paul Friedrich 
Meyerheim.
Cinderella was based off of a very old european folk tale about a princess' 
shoe.
Aladdin was based off of a part of Ludwig Fulda's 'Aladin Und Die 
Wunderlampe'.
Beauty and the Beast was a novel by Jeanne Marie Leprince de Beaumont.

As you can see, Disney never makes any originals - they're always a copy of 
something.
comments.author: Zeki Xu

comments.text:
+Zane Kuro

Oh, no, Russia has nothing of the sort like the Great Firewall. It is a far 
more subtle censorship. As part of the infamous legislation from a few 
years back that requires all blogs and similar internet postings with over 
3000 readers to be "truth-checked" by the government to combat "foreign 
influences and propaganda", no blogs with over 3000 readers or 
Russian-registered websites with over 100.000 visitors per month are 
allowed to link to non-Russian news sites without permission.
At the same time, the government funds "native" social media websites like 
VKontakte that are hardly used outside Russia, both because they can easily 
outcompete Western alternatives like Facebook in a still Western-sceptical 
country like Russia, and because they don't need to pay to spy on you if 
the site is Russian, like they would have with foreign social media.
Of the major foreign sites that are established within Russia, they usually 
have to abide by restrictions to what content they can show to Russian IPs, 
e.g. Google have to put anti-Kreml articles further back in google search 
results. This can create somewhat odd situations in cities near the 
borders, for example in Murmansk, where the closeness to Norway means that 
on different times of day you can open relatively pro-American sites like 
Yahoo News and see "Modern fascism: the dangers of Ukraine" at one point 
and "Pro-Russian Donbass separatists execute 56, arrest 400 over 
'encouragement of Ukrainian culture and similar traitorous acts'" later.
Hardware-wise the Russian government endeavors to have as many servers 
based in Russia as possible, to give the FSB free access to the information 
of the users. It is also an added security if Russia cuts itself off from 
the internet, like Putin has threatened several times over the last two 
decades. By having as much information as possible stored on local servers 
the RuNet would keep functioning without the rest of the body of the 
Internet, although sites like Google and Youtube would be non-functional, 
of course.

The latest addition to the internet restrictions is the requirement to give 
personal information when logging on to a public network, which ostensibly 
is an anti info-theft measure. In reality it exists to monitor those 
accessing the Deep Web to bypass FSB and Ministry of Information 
monitoring, for example the more anti-Putin, potentially-revolutionary 
parts of the Communist Party and hacker groups like Anonymous, which 
recently humiliated Kreml by hacking and releasing the real results of the 
referendum in Krim to join Russia (Russia still won the referendum, mind 
you, but only by a slight majority roughly equal to the amount of Russians 
living there, and less than half a million voted as opposed to the official 
number of 1.8 million, which caused huge embarrassment because the Kreml 
had publicly declared the rather ridiculous 97% vote to be true nine months 
ago, if you remember).

All of this makes sense, of course. By allying with the LDPR, Yedinaya 
Rossiya has enough votes in the Duma to pass what laws they want, so moves 
to make Russia more cut off from Western influences are natural given 
Putin's dwindling support in recent years. With Gorbachev and the other 
social democrats hating him for refusing to cooperate or even join the 
West, with the Communists hating him because of his oligarch friends 
(although nowadays they fear him rather than love him after he arrested 
several of them for trying to replace him with Mikhail Khodorkovski), and 
with the tsarists (there's oddly many of those around the last few years, I 
think their support might have increased after the Baltics went West) 
hating him for being a former KGB torturer (or at least, that's what they 
say he was; more realistically he was in charge of exposing Western agents, 
they just connect him with torture because he was always around when they 
were dragged off for counterrevolutionary activities), Putin's support has 
been dwindling the last few years. He only barely won the last election, 
despite it being rigged in several republics. Operation Terrakota (the 
swift military occupation of Krim followed by a replacing of the local 
Party of Regions government with one loyal to Russia and a snap referendum 
of joining the Federation), too, was as much an attempt to boost Putin's 
popularity as for the oil most Westerners think he was after.

comments.text:
I'm sure there have been a lot of people who have been offended. Everything 
makes somebody offended, whether the thing is a joke or not. In this case, 
the songs are the things, and are jokes. In the first part, the songs are 
pretty accurate historically. Native Americans were treated horribly by 
European settlers and some fought back. There are environmental problems, 
hence Ariel; the problem between the U.S. And the mid. East was pretty 
serious, and so on. This version is a bit more offensive, sure. But it's 
accurate, to a point. Mulan- transsexuality is a normal thing. Cinderella- 
There weren't medical advances, nor proper sciences, in her time period so 
killing her for being insane is quite true. Tiana- Katrina was a wreck. The 
entire situation. And unfortunately, many peoples' lives were destroyed 
and/or taken. The Elsa one is a bit of a stretch, and isn't anything 
historical, but if she became evil, this could happen. It's an alternative 
WWII universe, you know?

I mean, what I'm getting at is, if people are insulted by this, they'll be 
insulted by most other things in day to day life. Especially on the 
Internet. These are just me thoughts, though.

+SuperTuskafka It's not making fun of them... Nowhere does he say anything 
negative against all of the Jewish people and others who were considered 
'imperfect,' he just mentions concentration camps, which were in use long 
before WW2 and are still afterwards, depending on your interpretation of 
places like Guantonimo Bay. Plus, America had concentration camps for the 
Japanese Americans, or just about any Asian American during WW2 too. If 
anything, when people make comments or allusions to the holocaust in media 
forms like this, they just raise awareness of it and remind people it 
happened. As a whole though, people need to stop being so touchy about the 
subject, yes it happened and yes it was absolutely horrible, but just 
because someone makes a joke or play-on words about it doesn't mean they're 
disrespecting the deceased in anyway.

comments.text:
+1PKFilms Wow. I am impressed. I am glad you have a passion for this like 
mine. And I am actually glad for your corrections. I know why he wrote the 
book and what its purpose was but that was not my point. I am glad you 
point it out though, because I was hasty with my writing and made it sound 
that way. Also, If you are really interested in this history, I suggest you 
read the book Hitler's War by Henry Turtledove. He writes fantastic 
historical fiction. I also disagree with you a tad on the military part. he 
let his generals do a lot of the work yes, and he was EXTREMELY good at 
manipulation as you said. But, if he wasn't at the head of his party and 
hadn't made some crucial decisions the war would have gone differently. as 
is, the continuous bombing of London and the blitzkrieg on France were two 
fantastic strategies (planned or not). Also, one of the main reasons that 
Hitler lost so badly in Russia was because he WASN'T leading his soldiers 
and being tactful. Stalin made it clear that deserters would be shot 
immediately after they turned to run and his men were ordered to charge 
until they broke German ranks. That is what I learned at least. If it 
weren't for his EPIC failure in Russia, Hitler could have very well taken 
over half the world, which is all he would need to get control over the 
rest, seeing as how the half he conquered led the world anyways. So, this 
is what I learned, but I bow before your knowledge source and intelligence. 
Again, Check out Turtledove, He has written many great books, but I loved 
Hitler's War.
comments.author: Andrew Shuffett

comments.text:
+Andrew Shuffett I know this comment is kind of old but I want to correct 
you here (no offence intended you are one of the best educated here) but 
Hitler didn't wrote "mein Kampf" to just write a book. It was a propaganda 
book there are many lies in there. For example a big part of book is about 
his time in WW1 (without which ww2 would have never happened). He wrote 
about him being a soldier and how he fought for his fatherland (not sure 
whether this is the right translation) but in reality he only ran around 
savely behind the front and delivered messages. Also I agree with you 
Hitler was a genius in a way but the most horrible one ever. But a lot of 
his (military) success either wasn't actually his or was pure luck but the 
propaganda made or all look like Hitler did everything. for example the 
famous blitzkrieg Viktory in France actually was mainly caused by soldiers 
not listening to orders . His true genius isn't strategy it is 
manipulation. If he would had went out to the evaluations and said well i 
am going to kill democracy, kill all non master race (I know it sounds 
weird but that is the 1 to 1 translation) people and I am going to start a 
second world war. There would have been now way he succeed not even with 
all his money. Of course the money was a important factor but still he 
manipulated on a scale like nothing has ever been before and (hopefully) 
will ever be. Also he really had a few psychological problems. He killed 
his family before he killed himself. Nobody would have ever put his family 
up on trial. Also he ordered to destroy all personal information about him 
so we (sadly) know very few. 
Now two things 
A: I knew I did quite a few mistakes but I am typing this on my phone at 
midnight and I generally do a lot of mistakes (I just overlook them)
And B I am quite good informed about this topic because I am from Germany 
(so I know all the original phrases and with the translations) and let me 
tell you here you learn so much about WW2 (especially if you are interested 
on history).For example these horrifying movies of the kzt were shown to me 
when Is nine years old in history class (half of my class left the room and 
went home that day and some even stayed home for two days) and I had dreams 
about it for months. I really think it is important to learn about these 
things but can't they show the kids the movies when they are like twelve 
and until then just inform the kids without pictures.. 
Well I am getting off topic. Sry about that and the long comment but this 
is important to me personally

comments.text:
+NixZuSagen Anyone who conflates Germans to Nazis is, in all honesty, an 
idiot. These are the same people, (in America at least) who think the US is 
100% responsible for allied WW2 victory. Anyone who uses stereotypes to 
judge a culture is a moron, but germany isn't the only one to be portrayed 
as such. A lot of the same people probably view Japan as the Land of 
Tentacles, France as the Land of Surrender, Britain as the Land of Tea etc. 
There are two different applications for stereotypes, however: One is 
humour, like in this video, and the second tends to be twats being twats. 
It's not as if anyone sees this video and thinks that that is the actual 
way it is; those beliefs (the second kind) are perpetuated by the people 
who believe them to be true in the first place. Of course, it's your right 
to not like this video, I'm not saying you should like it or you have to 
like it, but, well, I like the whole video, and the Heil Elsa line is 
probably my favourite part overall.

kidnaps a small child whom then has to be rescued by his close friend. The 
story has been made into a movie before Frozen, a cartoon movie from Soviet 
in 1957, a tip for anyone of a darker mood. Frozen was then created as a 
more friendly way of doing it, since the original had no team sister force 
and was also sort of gritty. The architecture in the movie is mainly based 
on old northern European/Scandinavian models. For instance, the stave 
church, which is held up by a series of carrying beams, which in turn gives 
the structure is characteristic appearance. The rest of the houses follows 
a standard european architecture, not enclosed to any country.

comments.text:
+Kyra Zimmer Well, only about 1/3 of who you are can really change at such 
a mentally developed age, if that.  This is because while 1/3 is defined 
through genetics, another third is set prior to the age of 5, where a 
majority of your brain's development takes place.  There are, of course, 
exceptions to this (particularly, brain damage), but this is the general 
rule.

Anyways, to backtrack back on topic, I should rephrase what I said in my 
post:

"This is coming from the base that the idea of gender (mental sex) 
*shouldn't* exist."
It is true that some people do treat it in a sense that it does exist, but 
this is where my OP comes from.
comments.author: Ingenium

comments.text:
+Ingenium "Also, you need to understand that my argument is coming from the 
base that differences in gender (mental sex) doesn't exist" well, as a 
trans person, I have to say that in my experience, there seems to be a 
difference. It at least feels different. And I mean more than just how 
people react to you (which would be just societal gender roles).

"This is, of course, unless I misunderstood your last sentence and you were 
pretty much saying the same thing I said." I did.

Because I think the psychological development is more important for who a 
person really is than the DNA, because DNA doesn't change, while your mind 
can.
comments.author: Kyra “nonchip” Zimmer

comments.text:
+Kyra Zimmer "so i inferred from that statement that there's a 33% chance 
my psychology defining itself as female is by genetics"

That is where your logic becomes flawed.  If 33% of you is defined through 
your DNA, this does not mean that there is a 33% chance for your 
"psychology [to] define itself as female."

Also, you need to understand that my argument is coming from the base that 
differences in gender (mental sex) doesn't exist (*true* equality, not to 
be confused with simply saying it's alright for a guy to do girl things), 
so that means that the only thing left to define if somebody is a man or 
female is their sex (physical sex), i.e. chromosomes.

Also, a little FYI: DNA for a person is always pretty much set in stone. 
 At least, with today's technology.  Yes, genetic modification does exist, 
but we are unable to do it to a fully developed organism (though we have 
successfully done it to human embryos, and can do things like change a 
child's hair color, eye color, etc. prior to birth).
This is, of course, unless I misunderstood your last sentence and you were 
pretty much saying the same thing I said.
comments.author: Ingenium

comments.text:
+Ingenium you said that 1/3 of what I am is defined by genetics. you said 
this includes 1/3 of psychology. so i inferred from that statement that 
there's a 33% chance my psychology defining itself as female is by 
genetics. I said nothing about those genes being the same as those in the 
chromosomes. Also I disagree with "chromosomes tell if you are a man or a 
woman", because I define people by their personality, which has developed 
through life, not by what might have been true at the time of birth, when 
the DNA was pretty much set in stone.
comments.author: Kyra “nonchip” Zimmer

comments.text:
+Kyra Zimmer Except you are misplacing what that 33% is.  The closest you 
could come to it with that argument is referencing the genes that control 
the hormones; which, though parts are on the same chromosome that tells you 
that you are a man and not a woman, are in different parts of your genetic 
structure than that which controls organ development.  Because of this, you 
saying that my logic is flawed due to this fact is, well, flawed.
comments.author: Ingenium

comments.text:
+Ingenium also, if the part about my genetics defining 1/3 of who i am 
psychologically, how do you know there's none of my genes defining me as 
female? if there were some (and there should be a statistical 33.33% chance 
of this being the case), and just some other gene was malfunctioning and 
producing the wrong organs, then your claim of "my genes define me as male, 
because some chromosomes made some organs grow the way they did" is flawed.
comments.author: Kyra “nonchip” Zimmer

comments.text:
+Kyra Zimmer I said that it was a combination of the two, but I also never 
said that it is solely 100% boy or 100% girl.  I simply said that in cases 
that you are born with a matching chromosome-organ pair (like a majority of 
the world), then that is the sex that you are: rather 100% boy or 100% girl.

In cases where somebody with XX genes but born with a penis, there is 
really only one cause to that which I can think of: it was originally going 
to be a male-female identical twin but re-combined *very* earlier in 
development (or something else that can cause the same effect).  I am not 
sure if this is the case, and if you know of anything that can prove that 
wrong then okay, but this is why I've come to that conclusion: genetics. 
 The DNA (chromosomes) is what defines who a person is physically.  With 
this in mind, it is impossible for somebody with 100% of their cells 
holding XX chromosomes to be male.  At least a portion of the cells 
(especially the ones located in the genitalia region) would have to be male 
cells (XY chromosomes).

you to do is explain to me how you define the sexes in a plain

comments.text:
+Sarah It's interesting, when you consider the characters themselves and 
how similar Anna and Else's situation is to many notable nobles and even 
monarchs in the real world's past, namely that they're both fairly immature 
and, more importantly, chronically incompetent at being rulers. Along with 
that neat little comparison, though, is a much bigger struggle throughout 
the movie; namely, Elsa finding out exactly where she's supposed to draw 
the line between how much she cares about herself versus how much she cares 
about others. Else had spent her whole life basically trying to become 
something she wasn't (or, perhaps more accurately, suppress what she really 
was) for the sake of other people, which, while probably admirable in its 
own right for a person in a position of authority, also had huge negative 
effects on her psyche and caused her to feel, among other things, worthless 
and self-dejecting. "Let It Go" could be considered negative, like you 
said, where she's putting herself above everybody else, but I also see it 
as a positive in some ways; she's basically making a necessary emotional 
development all in one leap that is normally made throughout one's entire 
life up to becoming an adult, which does involve overshooting the mark and 
having to dial it back until you find a balance. The key struggle in Frozen 
isn't exactly geared around learning love and compassion for others, but in 
a significant way it's also about the struggle between a person's 
responsibilities and their need to stay human. And if you think about it, 
Elsa is certainly going to be a significantly better and more confident 
ruler after the events of the movie than she would have been if they hadn't 
happened.

Just food for thought.
comments.author: HeliosKitty

comments.text:
That was actually kinda the point of *Frozen*: Elsa is a subversion of the 
Evil Snow Queen archetype of classic fairy tales. Like *Maleficent* and the 
upcoming *Cruella*, Disney's new favorite trick seems to be humanizing the 
classic stories of evil women. As inspiring as it was, "Let it go" is all 
about no longer paying attention to the needs and rules of society: she's 
putting her needs and wishes above those of everybody else. The upbeat 
phrasing makes it sound admirable, but a monstrous narcissist might sing 
the very same song. Elsa *is* a villain—but one that we relate to and who 
eventually comes back to the light.
